Suppose the software architect is working on a program for simulating the behavior of a system of $n$ particles. Each particle $i$ has a position vector in 3-dimensional space, given by $\vec{r}_i (t) = \begin{pmatrix} x_i(t) \\ y_i(t) \\ z_i(t) \end{pmatrix}$.

The movement of each particle is governed by the following system of differential equations: 

\begin{align*}
\frac{d^2x_i(t)}{dt^2} &= -\sum_{j=1, j\neq i}^{n} \frac{Gm_j(x_i(t)-x_j(t))}{\left\| \vec{r}_i (t)-\vec{r}_j (t) \right\|^3}, \\
\frac{d^2y_i(t)}{dt^2} &= -\sum_{j=1, j\neq i}^{n} \frac{Gm_j(y_i(t)-y_j(t))}{\left\| \vec{r}_i (t)-\vec{r}_j (t) \right\|^3}, \\
\frac{d^2z_i(t)}{dt^2} &= -\sum_{j=1, j\neq i}^{n} \frac{Gm_j(z_i(t)-z_j(t))}{\left\| \vec{r}_i (t)-\vec{r}_j (t) \right\|^3}, \\
\end{align*}

where $G$ is the gravitational constant, $m_j$ is the mass of particle $j$, $x_i(t)$, $y_i(t)$, and $z_i(t)$ are the $x$, $y$, and $z$ coordinates of particle $i$ at time $t$, respectively, and $\left\| \vec{r}_i (t)-\vec{r}_j (t) \right\|$ is the Euclidean distance between particles $i$ and $j$ at time $t$.

Let $F_i(t) = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{d^2x_i(t)}{dt^2} \\ \frac{d^2y_i(t)}{dt^2} \\ \frac{d^2z_i(t)}{dt^2} \end{pmatrix}$ be the force experienced by particle $i$ at time $t$. 

Prove that for any time $t$,

\begin{equation*}
\sum_{i=1}^{n} m_i F_i(t) = \vec{0}.
\end{equation*}
